Practical Lab 3 - Univariate Linear Regresion:¶

In this lab you will train your first machine learning model in our course - a univariate linear regression model. You are asked to run a linear regression between the median house value (dependent variable) and each of the following independent variables.

  • You should run three models, one for each independent variable:
    • median income
    • population
    • number of households

Format your HTML as a short report.¶

  • It should be divided into short sections, each one with a Markdown title:

    • Framing the Problem - Describe the goal of this report (0.4 point).
    • Getting the Data - hyperlinking to the source (0.1 point) and loading into Pandas (0.1 point).
    • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):
      1. Explore statistics (e.g. using Pandas describe function) (0.2 point)
      2. Describe the 4 variables used in this lab. Review the range of the data for each variable, and other issues you notice (0.3 point)
      3. Create three Seaborn scatter plots of median house value vs. median income, population and number of households. There should be one scatter plot per each independent variable. Add a title to each graph (using Seaborn). Provide textual review of what you see in these graphs (relevant insights). (0.6 points).
    • Run three linear regressions (fitting) between (1.2 points):
      1. median house value vs. median income.
      2. median house value vs. population.
      3. median house value vs. number of households.
    • Summarize in a table, for each of the three models:
      1. intercept and slope (0.5 point).
      2. Mean Squared Error - the loss (0.3 point).
      3. Mean Absolute Error (0.3 point).
    • Plot the resulting line on top of the scatter data for each of the three models (three separate graphs) (1 point).
    • Provide a conclusion about the goodness-of-fit, and other insights you might have (1 point).

This folowing code is explanation :

  • matplotlib library to create a histogram for each numerical column in a DataFrame named 'housing'.
  • housing.hist(): This method generates histograms for all numerical columns in the DataFrame 'housing'.
  • figsize=(12, 10): This parameter sets the size of the figure (width, height) in inches. In this case, the figure will be 12 inches wide and 10 inches high.
  • bins=30: This parameter determines the number of bins (intervals) in the histogram. In this case, each histogram will have 30 bins.
  • edgecolor="pink": This parameter sets the color of the edges of the bars in the histogram to pink.
  • Adjusting Subplots> plt.subplots_adjust(): This function adjusts the subplot parameters.
    • hspace=0.7: This sets the height spacing between subplots to 0.7 times the height of one subplot. It creates vertical space between the histograms.
    • wspace=0.4: This sets the width spacing between subplots to 0.4 times the width of one subplot. It creates horizontal space between the histograms.

We can see that:

  • the dataset contains 20,640 samples and 8 features;

  • all features are numerical features encoded as floating number;

  • there is no missing values.

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

# Create a DataFrame to store the summary
summary_data = {
    'Model': ['Median Income', 'Population', 'Number of Households'],
    'Intercept': [],
    'Slope': [],
    'Mean Squared Error': [],
    'Mean Absolute Error': []
}

# Function to calculate metrics and update the summary
def update_summary(model, independent_variable, y_true):
    y_pred = model.predict(independent_variable)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)

    summary_data['Intercept'].append(model.intercept_)
    summary_data['Slope'].append(model.coef_[0])
    summary_data['Mean Squared Error'].append(mse)
    summary_data['Mean Absolute Error'].append(mae)

# Update summary for Median Income model
update_summary(model_income, X_income, y)

# Update summary for Population model
update_summary(model_population, X_population, y)

# Update summary for Number of Households model
update_summary(model_households, X_households, y)

# Create a DataFrame from the summary data
summary_df = pd.DataFrame(summary_data)

# Print the summary table
print(summary_df)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Function to plot scatter data and regression line
def plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model, independent_variable, y_true, title):
    # Scatter plot
    sns.scatterplot(x=independent_variable.iloc[:, 0], y=y_true, label='Actual Data')

    # Regression line
    x_range = independent_variable.iloc[:, 0]
    y_pred = model.predict(independent_variable)
    plt.plot(x_range, y_pred, color='red', label='Regression Line')

    # Set plot properties
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(independent_variable.columns[0])
    plt.ylabel('Median House Value')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Plot for Median Income model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_income, X_income, y, 'Median Income vs. Median House Value')

# Plot for Population model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_population, X_population, y, 'Population vs. Median House Value')

# Plot for Number of Households model
plot_scatter_with_regression_line(model_households, X_households, y, 'Number of Households vs. Median House Value')

Interpreting the goodness-of-fit and gaining insights from linear regression models involves analyzing various metrics and visualizations. Below are some key considerations based on the information obtained from the linear regression models:

Goodness-of-Fit Metrics:

Intercept and Slope: Examine the intercept and slope values for each model. The intercept represents the predicted median house value when the independent variable is zero, and the slope indicates the change in the median house value for a one-unit change in the independent variable. Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Assess the values of MSE and MAE for each model. Lower values of these metrics suggest better model performance. They quantify the average squared and absolute differences between predicted and actual median house values, respectively. Scatter Plots and Regression Lines:

Visual Inspection: Look at the scatter plots with the overlaid regression lines. Assess how well the regression line fits the scatter data. A good fit is indicated by the line closely following the trend of the data points. Outliers: Identify any outliers in the scatter plots. Outliers can disproportionately influence the regression model, so understanding their impact is crucial. Statistical Significance:

Coefficient Significance: Evaluate the statistical significance of the coefficients. If the p-values associated with the coefficients are small, it suggests that the corresponding independent variables are likely significant predictors of the median house value. Overall Conclusion:

Model Comparison: Compare the three models based on their goodness-of-fit metrics. Consider which independent variable appears to be the most influential in predicting median house value. Insights: Draw insights from the results. For example, if median income has a strong positive correlation with median house value, it suggests that areas with higher median incomes tend to have higher house values. Conversely, a negative correlation might indicate that as certain factors increase, median house values decrease. In summary, a comprehensive analysis involves a combination of quantitative metrics and visual inspection. Assess the goodness-of-fit, statistical significance of coefficients, and draw meaningful insights from the relationships observed in the data. Additionally, consider the limitations of linear regression and whether the assumptions of the model are met.
